{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"519"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/519"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.13,0.15,0.03,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107509"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"434"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39854"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increased difficulty reading. Despite new reading glasses six months ago, her eyesight has deteriorated progressively. Sunlight adversely affects her vision much more than it used to. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes but does not have regular follow-up. She does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On Snellen chart testing, her visual acuity in both eyes is 6/18 and this is reduced to 6/24 when the background lighting is increased. Her right eye is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phacoemulsification","Anti-vascular endothelial growth factor injection","Laser photocoagulation","Topical pilocarpine","Laser trabeculoplasty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows opacity of the ocular lens characteristic of a cataract. This diagnosis is supported by the history of progressive, bilateral vision loss exacerbated by light, with diabetes mellitus and age being relevant risk factors. While the history of poorly managed diabetes mellitus may suggest an element of diabetic retinopathy, the history and image are more in keeping with cataract disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhacoemulsification\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard treatment for cataracts. This procedure involves breaking up the lens using ultrasound energy, aspirating the fragments, and inserting a synthetic intraocular lens. Her fundus needs to be checked for diabetic retinopathy and if present, managed prior to cataract surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-vascular endothelial growth factor injection\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat age-related macular degeneration and diabetic macular oedema, not cataracts. This treatment would not address the lens opacity causing her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat diabetic retinopathy by sealing leaking blood vessels in the retina. While this patient has diabetes, her presentation is consistent with cataract rather than diabetic retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical pilocarpine\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the emergency treatment of acute angle closure glaucoma to constrict the pupil and open the drainage angle. This patient shows no signs of acute glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser trabeculoplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat primary open angle glaucoma by improving drainage of aqueous humour. This patient\u0027s presentation is not consistent with glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Phacoemulsification followed by intraocular lens implant is the standard treatment for cataracts.","Cataracts present with progressive vision loss that worsens in bright light, often with glare sensitivity.","Diabetic patients require fundoscopic examination to exclude diabetic retinopathy before cataract surgery."],"references":["Preferred Practice Patterns: Cataract and Intraocular Lens Surgery [Internet]. 2016. Available from: https://ranzco.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/RANZCO-Cataract-PPP-2016.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"519"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19891"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19891"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71d232f9-f8e1-40b0-aced-06f0e71081e3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71d232f9-f8e1-40b0-aced-06f0e71081e3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":359,"height":246}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T20:03:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T20:08:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107509"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmol